ID: B3-Ch02c-River
TEXT:

#if(v_b3_ch2_question == 0) {
 "I have to admit that I was wondering how Kelrim got to learn white magic."

"I learned it mostly from books," Kelrim says. "Goblins don't typically practice healing magic, so I didn't have anyone to teach me. The standard white mage spellbook helped me a lot in the beginning, but I've read many other books as well, and in time, I also began to experiment, making small modifications to certain spells, in order to see what they would result in. Unfortunately, I am only a novice spell caster, so a lot of these experiments ended up in failure."

"If you've managed to modify any sort of spells successfully, then I'd say that you are quite far from being a novice mage," Illuna says. "Most beginner mages would rarely bother casting any other spells than the most basic ones, and they most certainly wouldn't risk modifying them."

"They wouldn't?..." Kelrim asks, surprised. "I always assumed that this was how everyone started learning how to use magic. Anyway, I had a question to ask you as well. You seem to have come to Ollendor recently. You wouldn't happen to have met a group of three goblins on your way here, would you? They were supposed to return to this city any day now, and I made sure to leave them this week's password written on a rock by the side of a river not far from here, but I haven't heard from them yet."

}
#if(v_b3_ch2_question == 1) {
 "Now that you mention it, I am a bit curious to know how a goblin ended up in a human city."

"It's not that much of a story to tell, really," Kelrim says. "A while ago, my friend and I heard that the city of Ollendor accepted goblins within its borders, so we decided to come here and try our luck. After living here for some time, my friend decided to go out in search for two older friends of ours that we left behind, in the hopes that he could convince them to come here as well. In the meantime, a lot of things have happened, and I eventually ended up joining the rebels, as you can see." 

He pauses.

"Speaking of my friends..." Kelrim continues. "You wouldn't happen to have run into a group of three goblins on your way here, would you? They were supposed to return to this city any day now, and I made sure to leave them this week's password written on a rock by the side of a river not far from here, but I haven't heard from them yet."

}
#if(v_b3_ch2_question == 2) {
 "Actually, I can't say that I care all that much, to be honest."

"That is understandable," Kelrim says. "You barely even know me, after all... However, if it's not too much trouble, there was a question that I wanted to ask you, since you seem to have come to Ollendor recently."

"Of course," Daren says. "What is it?"

"You wouldn't happen to have met a group of three goblins on your way here, would you?" Kelrim says. "They were supposed to return to this city any day now, and I made sure to leave them this week's password written on a rock by the side of a river not far from here, but I haven't heard from them yet."

}
#if(v_b3_ch2_goblins == 1) {
 "Those goblins that you speak of..." Daren says, looking a bit shaken. "Would they have been wearing some really basic equipment? Like cheap leather armor and some really worn down weapons? Was one of them considerably older than the other two?"

"Yes, that's them!" Kelrim says. "You've met them, then?"

"Yes, but..." Daren says, struggling to find his words. "We... killed them. We killed them all. We thought that they were with Tyrath. Kelrim, I'm so sorry, we didn't think that... We just..."

While Daren is still trying to find his words, Kelrim looks as if he is only now slowly beginning to fully grasp what has been said to him.

"My friends are... dead?" Kelrim says, with great pain in his voice, as he is now looking straight ahead of him, almost as if he has forgotten that there is anyone else in the room now beside him.

The goblin's knees then begin to tremble, and as he loses the strength to even stand up, he takes a step back and he drops into one of the chairs behind him, without uttering another word. In the meantime, Kate looks as if she's having a little crisis herself. She is sweating very hard, and she is staring straight at the ground, looking as if she were about to have a mental breakdown.

 That's right... Kate killed one of Kelrim's friends herself. She must be behaving this way because of the guilt she's feeling after she saw the goblin react to his friends' deaths.

"Kelrim..." Daren says. "I didn't know... I..."

"No, it's alright," Kelrim says, as he tries hard to regain his composure, although if you were to judge from the look he now has in his eyes, you would think that he hasn't slept at all for three days straight. "I'm not blaming you. They were goblins, after all... You had no reason to think twice before killing them. Who knows? If they were different goblins, they might even have killed you, if you didn't attack them first... I know that this is how the world works, but still... I... just need a few moments to recollect myself, that's all..."

Hearing the goblin's words seems to have pushed Kate even further over the edge. Her eyes are blinking rapidly, and she looks as if she is quickly panicking.

"Kate, are you with me?" I ask her, as I place myself in front of her. "Kate!"

Kate raises her eyes from the ground, but she doesn't answer, now looking at me with the same panicked expression that she was having before. 

As I am still busy trying to get Kate to snap out of it, Breynan suddenly turns around and then he jumps back, out of shock, now looking at a man in his mid-fifties standing in front of him, who is wearing chainmail armor and a gray mantle around his shoulders.

}
#if(v_b3_ch1_password == 1 && v_b3_ch2_goblins == 0) {
 "Did the writing on that rock say 'griffin beak' by any chance?" I say.

"No," Kelrim says. "I mean, yes, that's what it technically says, but you are not meant to read the writing as it is. You are supposed to rearrange the symbols, using a secret code known only by me and my friends, and if you do that, the password it gives you is 'gargoyle wings'. But how do you know what was written on the rock?"

"Well..." I say. "It turns out that our friend Melindra over here took that rock to add it to her collection."

"What?..." Melindra says. "No, there was no writing on any of my rocks!"

"As you can see, she didn't know about the writing," I say. "She only picked up the rock by accident."

"Hey!" Melindra says. "I said there was nothing written on any of the rocks! Don't ignore me!"

"But then... if they don't have the rock, it means that my friends are just stuck outside, unable to get into the city!" Kelrim says, as Melindra is pouting in the background.

"Yeah, they're most definitely outside," I say. "Some goblins tried calling out to us before we got here, but we just ignored them and went on our way."

"I see..." Kelrim says. "In that case, I will have to go out and look for them later."

}
#if(v_b3_ch1_password == 0 && v_b3_ch2_goblins == 0) {
 "We did run into some goblins on our way here, actually," I say. "They wanted to discuss something with us about the password required to enter the city, but we just ignored them and went on our way."

"I see..." Kelrim says. "Those must have been my friends. I don't see why any other goblins would be hanging out near the city. I will have to go out and look for them later."

}
#if(v_b3_ch2_goblins == 2) {
 "We did run into some goblins on our way here, actually," I say. "We had a little chat with them about that very rock you were talking about. Apparently they didn't find it on the side of the river, and they thought that we were the ones who took it. Anyway, they're probably still waiting in the forest outside the village, since I doubt they could have gotten inside the city through any other means."

"I see..." Kelrim says. "In that case, I will have to go out and look for them later."

}
#if(v_b3_ch2_goblins == 3) {
 "We did run into some goblins on our way here, actually," I say. "We had a little chat with them about that very rock you were talking about. It turned out that we had taken it by accident, so we traded them the password written on it in exchange for them telling us that we needed to wink three times at the guard, for him to let us through. I'm sure that your friends must have already entered the city by now."

"Oh my..." Kelrim says. "In that case, they must already be waiting for me at our meeting spot. I will have to go there as soon as possible."

}
#if(v_b3_ch2_goblins == 4) {
 "We did run into some goblins on our way here, actually," I say. "We had a little chat with them about that very rock you were talking about. It turned out that we had taken it by accident, so we traded them the password written on it in exchange for them telling us that we needed to wink three times at the guard, for him to let us through. Your friends entered the city shortly before us, so they should be hanging around somewhere on the surface right now."

